Oliver Marks spoke:

<snap>

>My code almost runs but does not jump the way i want it is only
>supposed to jump if one number is higher than the other but instead it jump 
>regardless

<snap>

>.assem
>         !INP
>         MOVE.b d0,d1          MOVE.b d0,d5
>         !INP
>         MOVE.b d0,d2
>         MOVE.b d0,d4
>         CMP.l d1,d2
>         BGT GREAT
>         MOVE.b d4,d0
>         !OUT
>         MOVE.b d5,d0
>         !OUT
>         NPrint "less"
>         RTS
>GREAT:  MOVE.b d5,d0
>         !OUT
>         MOVE.b d4,d0
>         !OUT
>         NPrint "greater"
>         RTS

Just a tad note, in macro INP, is "num" a quick/float/byte/word or a 
longword? This is important to know.

I'm not able to execute your code right now, but when .assem is executed, 
the line "MOVE.b d0,d1" etc only copies a byte from d0 to d1, however when 
executing "CMP.l d1,d2", d1 and d2 compares a whole longword, not just only 
just a byte of d2 with d1.

So, check what values are getting stored in d0 and d1 before executing the 
comparsion and if it's a quick/float/byte/word or a longword. If you're 
using "CMP.l" you need to be sure that the upper 7 bytes of d1/d2 are 
containing the same values (in this case zero is preffered), thus the CMP.l 
should give the correct result.

Excuse me if this was weird understanging, It's only 8 in the mornin' and 
I'm deadly tired - darn Robert Jordan writing good books =)

//Thor


