@NODE "Mail_650" "Re: Shapes, Windows and Blitting"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 25 May 1999 09:35:25 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 25 May 1999 09:34:08 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Shapes, Windows and Blitting



> do this, I need a way of blitting shapes to an OS window. Is there a
> version of WBlit equivalent to BBlit (so that smooth movement of the sha=
pe
> can happen without leaving a trail as WBlit does), or otherwise, how can=
 I

Don't think so.

> use a bitmap attached to the window to blit to. I don't like the second
> method, as I would have to set up a gadgetlist, wasting a bit of memory,
> to be able to attach a bitmap to the window. (All because of the argumen=
ts
> of the Window command)

OK, don't bother with the bitmap and gadgetlist parameters of the window. =
When 
you want to draw a bitmap to a window you can use the command:

BltBitMapRastPort_ Addr BitMap(bmp),x1,y1,RastPort(win),x2,y2,w,h,$C0

bmp =3D number of bitmap you want to draw
x1,y1 =3D co-ordinates in bitmap to start drawing from
win =3D window number to draw to
x2,y2 =3D co-ordinates in window to start drawing to
w,h =3D width and height of the area to draw


